article.description:
Nykesha Sales scored 25 points, and Shannon
Johnson added 24 to lead the Orlando Miracle to a 70-55 victory
Tuesday night over the Washington Mystics.
article.headline: Big first half gets Orlando rolling
article.linkText: Sales and Johnson power Miracle's victory over Mystics
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nykesha Sales scored 25 points, and Shannon Johnson added 24 to lead the Orlando Miracle to a 70-55 victory Tuesday night over the Washington Mystics. Sales and Johnson, who together average 30 points, scored 36 of the Miracle's 38 first-half points. Orlando (12-13) scored the game's first 14 points and had an 18-2 lead with 14:19 to play in the first half. Washington (15-10) never caught up. ''From start to finish, that was probably our best game of the year,'' Miracle coach Dee Brown said. Johnson began the game with a jumper and quickly added a 3-pointer. Sales and Johnson hit two more 3s, and Sales converted a three-point play to make it 14-0. After a layup by Chamique Holdsclaw with 16:27 to play gave Washington its first points, Sales hit two more jumpers. Johnson converted a three-point play to give Orlando its biggest lead, 21-4. ''On offense, we took the ball at them. Our team set some very good screens. I came off screens just wide open,'' Johnson said. Brown was especially pleased at the first-half domination by Sales and Johnson. ''That's what they're All-Stars for,'' he said. ''It was things they did on defense that got us shots. When you have two All-Stars, you expect them to play like that every night, (but) you don't expect them to have all your points.'' Orlando held Washington to a season-low 31.5 percent shooting. The Mystics trailed only 38-30 at halftime, and then cut the deficit to six points when Holdsclaw made a layup to start the second half. But Sales hit a running jump, Katie Douglas made a jumper and Johnson hit two free throws to make it 45-32. ''We didn't want to do any stupid things or take any crazy shots,'' Sales said of the second half. ''The first five minutes of the first half, and the first five minutes of the second half were the most important part of the game,'' Brown said. Stacey Dales-Schuman's 3-pointer, and baskets by Asjha Jones and two from Holdsclaw cut the Orlando advantage to 45-41. Led by three consecutive jumpers by Adrienne Johnson, the Miracle put the game away with a 15-5 run to make it 60-46 with 2:06 left. Washington, which began the season 9-1, lost for the fourth consecutive time, and fell into a first-place tie for the Eastern Conference lead with New York. ''We just need to find our focus again. We've strayed. We need an attitude check,'' Mystics coach Marianne Stanley said. ''We had people lose their poise. People got flustered. We didn't all of a sudden get stupid basketball-wise.'' Holdsclaw, playing her second game after missing the previous nine because of a sprained left ankle, led the Mystics with 18 points. ''Obviously, we're pressing. We're trying to find right now what works,'' Holdsclaw said. Notes
Sales tied her career high with four steals for Orlando, which won its second consecutive on the road after losing seven in a row. ... The 15-point margin of defeat was Washington's largest of the season.
